casebody.data:
Christopher G. HICKS, Plaintiff—Appellant, v. COMMISSIONER, SOCIAL SECURITY ADMINISTRATION, Defendant—Appellee. No. 07-1171. United States Court of Appeals, Fourth Circuit. Submitted: Sept. 19, 2007. Decided: Oct. 10, 2007. George L. Fitzgerald, Charlotte, North Carolina, for Appellant. Gretchen C.F. Shappert, United States Attorney, Sidney P. Alexander, Assistant United States Attorney, Dino Trubiano, Special Assistant United States Attorney, Robert J. Triba, Social Security Administration, Boston, Massachusetts, for Appellee.

Before WILKINSON, MOTZ, and SHEDD, Circuit Judges.

Affirmed by unpublished PER CURIAM opinion.

Unpublished opinions are not binding precedent in this circuit.

PER CURIAM:

Christopher G. Hicks appeals the district court’s order dismissing this action for lack of subject matter jurisdiction. We have reviewed the record and find no reversible error. Accordingly, we affirm for the reasons stated by the district court. Hicks v. Commissioner, No. l:06-cv-00222 (W.D.N.C. Jan. 24, 2007). We dispense with oral argument because the facts and legal contentions are adequately presented in the materials before the court and argument would not aid the decisional process.

AFFIRMED.
